FoodHub Data Analysis¶

Context¶

The number of restaurants in New York is increasing day by day. Lots of students and busy professionals rely on those restaurants due to their hectic lifestyles. Online food delivery service is a great option for them. It provides them with good food from their favorite restaurants. A food aggregator company FoodHub offers access to multiple restaurants through a single smartphone app.

The app allows the restaurants to receive a direct online order from a customer. The app assigns a delivery person from the company to pick up the order after it is confirmed by the restaurant. The delivery person then uses the map to reach the restaurant and waits for the food package. Once the food package is handed over to the delivery person, he/she confirms the pick-up in the app and travels to the customer's location to deliver the food. The delivery person confirms the drop-off in the app after delivering the food package to the customer. The customer can rate the order in the app. The food aggregator earns money by collecting a fixed margin of the delivery order from the restaurants.

Objective¶

The food aggregator company has stored the data of the different orders made by the registered customers in their online portal. They want to analyze the data to get a fair idea about the demand of different restaurants which will help them in enhancing their customer experience. Suppose you are hired as a Data Scientist in this company and the Data Science team has shared some of the key questions that need to be answered. Perform the data analysis to find answers to these questions that will help the company to improve the business.

Data Description¶

The data contains the different data related to a food order. The detailed data dictionary is given below.

Data Dictionary¶

  • order_id: Unique ID of the order
  • customer_id: ID of the customer who ordered the food
  • restaurant_name: Name of the restaurant
  • cuisine_type: Cuisine ordered by the customer
  • cost: Cost of the order
  • day_of_the_week: Indicates whether the order is placed on a weekday or weekend (The weekday is from Monday to Friday and the weekend is Saturday and Sunday)
  • rating: Rating given by the customer out of 5
  • food_preparation_time: Time (in minutes) taken by the restaurant to prepare the food. This is calculated by taking the difference between the timestamps of the restaurant's order confirmation and the delivery person's pick-up confirmation.
  • delivery_time: Time (in minutes) taken by the delivery person to deliver the food package. This is calculated by taking the difference between the timestamps of the delivery person's pick-up confirmation and drop-off information

# This study shows the distribution of repeated orders in "customer_id"
# Get counts for each customer ID
customer_counts = df["customer_id"].value_counts()
# Get counts of their frequencies
frequency_counts = customer_counts.value_counts().sort_index()

# Plotting with barplot()
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
plot = sns.barplot(x=frequency_counts.index, y=frequency_counts.values)
# For loop will add the count on top of each bar
for i, count in enumerate(frequency_counts.values):
    plot.text(i, count + 0.1, str(count), ha="center", va="bottom")
#Adding labels
plt.xlabel("Number of times ordered by same customer")
plt.ylabel("Count of unique customer_id")
plt.title("Count of unique customers and repeated orders")
plt.show()

There are 1200 unique customer IDs in the dataset.

An analysis of the number of customers that have repeatedly used FoodHub service has revealed a very right skewed distribution, with 784 users using the service only once, representing about 65.3% of all users. The other 34.7% of users have used the service more than once, with 267 customers ordering twice from the service, which is an expressive 22% of total customers in the dataset.

The analysis of correlation between numeric features in the dataset reveals that:¶

Observations:¶

  • There is slight negative correlation (-0.03) between cost_of_the_order x delivery_time.
  • There is slight positive correlation (0.03) between cost_of_the_order x rating, perhaps indicating users that spend more are likely to score a higher rating.
  • There is slight positive correlation (0.04) between cost_of_the_order x food_preparation_time, perhaps because the larger the cost, the more items the order has.
  • There is a slight positive correlation (0.02) between "order_id" and "cost_of_the_order". If "order_id" in the system is generated in an increasing order, it perhaps indicates that as the platform grows, people are more confident in spending more with large orders.

Overall, the correlations are not significant, indicating a weak linear relationship between the variables.¶

Conclusion and Recommendations¶

Conclusions:¶

Technical analysis of the data:¶

  1. Data quality:
  • Data provided by FoodHub was in good condition for the analysis, with no missing data.
  1. Univariate Analysis:
  • Customer analysis reveals 1200 unique customers.
  • Restaurant analysis identifies 178 unique restaurants.
  • Cuisine analysis shows American cuisine is the most popular.
  • Cost analysis indicates a median order cost of $14.14.
  • Day analysis reveals 71.2% of orders are placed on weekends.
  • Rating analysis shows 38% of orders are not rated.
  • Food preparation time has a median of 27 minutes.
  • Delivery time has a median of 25 minutes.
  1. Customer statistics:
  • Top 5 restaurants by order count are ShakeShack, TheMeatballShop, BlueRibbonSushi, BlueRibbonFriedChicken, and Parm.
  • Analysis of customer loyalty shows a majority (65.3%) order only once, indicating potential for targeted promotions to increase repeat orders.
  1. Multivariate Analysis:
  • Correlation analysis reveals weak relationships among numeric features.
  • Visual analysis by weekdays and weekends shows consistent patterns.
  • Cuisine type and preparation time analysis suggests turnover efficiency for specific cuisines, more specifically Spanish and Korean.
  • Cuisine type and user rating analysis reveal potential areas for improvement in terms of diversity of restaurant options and their food quality.
  1. Delivery Time Analysis:
  • About 10.54% of orders take more than 60 minutes to deliver.
  • Mean delivery time is lower on weekends (22.47 minutes) compared to weekdays (28.34 minutes).

Recommendations:¶

  • Customer Engagement: Introduce loyalty programs or exclusive offers for repeat customers to increase retention. The majority of orders are placed on weekends, suggesting focused marketing efforts on weekdays can boost order counts.

  • Restaurant Collaboration: Establish partnerships with top restaurants for mutual promotion and increased visibility. Encourage restaurants to maintain high ratings to be eligible for promotional offers and encourage customer to rate their orders.

  • Cuisine Diversity: American cuisine is the most popular but diversifying cuisine options could attract a broader customer base. Encourage a diverse range of cuisines to attract a wider audience. Promote less popular cuisines to increase their visibility and customer base (e.g. Korean and Vietnamese).

  • Operational Efficiency: Work with restaurants with efficient food preparation times to enhance overall delivery speed (e.g. Spanish and Korean). Efficient turnover for specific cuisines suggests potential for collaboration with faster-preparing restaurants. Implement measures to ensure timely deliveries for customer satisfaction.

  • Marketing Strategy: Leverage customer ratings and feedback to improve overall service quality. Insights from multivariate analysis may help tailor marketing strategies for specific cuisines.

  • Revenue Optimization: Explore revenue-sharing models to incentivize restaurants with higher order costs. Offer discounts during peak hours to encourage more orders.

  • Customer Communication: Encourage customers to provide ratings and feedback through incentives.

By implementing these recommendations, FoodHub can enhance customer satisfaction, attract more restaurants, and optimize revenue streams. Regular data monitoring and feedback analysis will be essential for continuous improvement.¶
